I&#39;m a lurker on the list, but thought I&#39;d chime in about this question.  I work as a conservator
(artwork on paper) by day, so safe storage is one thing we&#39;re concerned about.  I&#39;d avoid using
any sort of curing latex or Styrofoam product.  Prolonged off-gassing can be a problem.  I&#39;m not
sure that the vapors will affect metal, but they will definitely affect silk. I&#39;d urge you to
consider getting in touch with an objects conservator at a major museum with tsuba in their
collection.  Perhaps the Museum of Fine Arts Boston, with which I am familiar.

As for foam, there is a safe foam on the market called &#39;Ethafoam&#39; made by Dow chemical.  There is
a company called Gaylord  (www.gaylord.com) which sells it but I am sure there are others.  It is
archivally sound and can be cut with scissors/knife to any shape.

-Doug Sanders
